			<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
		
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>Major Iranian Ballistic Missile Bases Sustain Critical Damage in Latest 48 Hours of Operation Roaring Lion</title>
		<link>https://israel-alma.org/major-iranian-ballistic-missile-bases-sustain-critical-damage-in-latest-48-hours-of-operation-roaring-lion/</link>
					<comments>https://israel-alma.org/major-iranian-ballistic-missile-bases-sustain-critical-damage-in-latest-48-hours-of-operation-roaring-lion/#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Alma Research]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 05 Mar 2026 18:20:29 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Alma's Blog]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Articles]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Iran]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Operation Roaring Lion]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://israel-alma.org/?p=53324</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Details on four of Iran&#8217;s largest ballistic missile bases hit by US-IDF airstrikes updated in the last 48 hours of Operation Roaring Lion (Analysis according to imagery by Sentinel-2 and Airbus– Visual aids are with pre-war imagery). Hajiabad &#8211; In Hormozgan province, this MRBM base was not targeted during operations in June 2025. At least [&#8230;]</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://israel-alma.org/major-iranian-ballistic-missile-bases-sustain-critical-damage-in-latest-48-hours-of-operation-roaring-lion/">Major Iranian Ballistic Missile Bases Sustain Critical Damage in Latest 48 Hours of Operation Roaring Lion</a> appeared first on <a href="https://israel-alma.org">Alma Research and Education Center</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>Details on four of Iran&#8217;s largest ballistic missile bases hit by US-IDF airstrikes updated in the last 48 hours of Operation Roaring Lion (Analysis according to imagery by Sentinel-2 and Airbus<br>– Visual aids are with pre-war imagery).</p>



<p>Hajiabad &#8211; In Hormozgan province, this MRBM base was not targeted during operations in June 2025. At least three mobile MRBM launchers have been destroyed above ground at the base as of 01 March 2026. This base has silos for underground launch capability.</p>



<ol class="wp-block-list"></ol>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img decoding="async" width="1024" height="576" src="https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/1-2-1024x576.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-53329" srcset="https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/1-2-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/1-2-300x169.jpg 300w, https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/1-2-768x432.jpg 768w, https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/1-2-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/1-2.jpg 1922w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<p>Dezful North &#8211; In Khuzestan province, this base sustained damage on the surface during operations in June 2025. The main exterior support site, which survived the June 2025 operation, has now been completely destroyed at some time between 01 and 03 March 2026.</p>



<ol class="wp-block-list"></ol>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="576" src="https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/2-1-1024x576.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-53326" srcset="https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/2-1-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/2-1-300x169.jpg 300w, https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/2-1-768x432.jpg 768w, https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/2-1-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/2-1.jpg 1922w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<p>Kermanshah North &#8211; In Kermanshah province, the tunnel entrances and structures outside them were hit with airstrikes during operations in June 2025. Since the start of operations on 28 February 2026, the entire exterior support site has been destroyed, and the entrances were once again targeted. Industrial construction equipment outside the base has also been destroyed.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="576" src="https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/3-1-1024x576.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-53327" srcset="https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/3-1-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/3-1-300x169.jpg 300w, https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/3-1-768x432.jpg 768w, https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/3-1-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/3-1.jpg 1922w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<p>Tabriz South &#8211; In East Azerbaijan province, this was heavily damaged during operations in June 2025. Targets in the most recent round of strikes include a Radome, the base air defense site, a tunnel entrance, a new facility which was under construction, and a structure in the administrative area.</p>



<ol class="wp-block-list"></ol>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="576" src="https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/4-1-1024x576.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-53328" srcset="https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/4-1-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/4-1-300x169.jpg 300w, https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/4-1-768x432.jpg 768w, https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/4-1-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://israel-alma.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/4-1.jpg 1922w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>
<p>The post <a href="https://israel-alma.org/major-iranian-ballistic-missile-bases-sustain-critical-damage-in-latest-48-hours-of-operation-roaring-lion/">Major Iranian Ballistic Missile Bases Sustain Critical Damage in Latest 48 Hours of Operation Roaring Lion</a> appeared first on <a href="https://israel-alma.org">Alma Research and Education Center</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
					<wfw:commentRss>https://israel-alma.org/major-iranian-ballistic-missile-bases-sustain-critical-damage-in-latest-48-hours-of-operation-roaring-lion/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
			<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
		
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>Hezbollah’s Anti‑Tank Missile Arsenal: Capabilities and Threat Assessment</title>
		<link>https://israel-alma.org/hezbollahs-anti-tank-missile-arsenal-capabilities-and-threat-assessment/</link>
					<comments>https://israel-alma.org/hezbollahs-anti-tank-missile-arsenal-capabilities-and-threat-assessment/#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Alma Research]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 05 Mar 2026 18:06:11 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Alma's Blog]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Articles]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Hezbollah]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Israel Northern Border]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Lebanon]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Operation Roaring Lion]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://israel-alma.org/?p=53321</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Within the framework of Hezbollah’s attacks against IDF forces and Israeli territory, it is, as expected, making use of anti-tank missiles. On March 4, it even succeeded in hitting an IDF force and wounding two soldiers. We do not have data regarding the quantities of anti-tank missiles currently in Hezbollah’s possession, but it can be [&#8230;]</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://israel-alma.org/hezbollahs-anti-tank-missile-arsenal-capabilities-and-threat-assessment/">Hezbollah’s Anti‑Tank Missile Arsenal: Capabilities and Threat Assessment</a> appeared first on <a href="https://israel-alma.org">Alma Research and Education Center</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>Within the framework of Hezbollah’s attacks against IDF forces and Israeli territory, it is, as expected, making use of anti-tank missiles. On March 4, it even succeeded in hitting an IDF force and wounding two soldiers. We do not have data regarding the quantities of anti-tank missiles currently in Hezbollah’s possession, but it can be estimated that the size of the arsenal, across the various missile types, stands at several thousand. This would allow Hezbollah to make prolonged use of them, provided operational conditions arise that enable launches. What types of anti-tank missiles can Hezbollah launch toward IDF forces along the line of contact and toward Israeli territory near the border?</p>



<p>Below is a breakdown of the anti-tank missiles in Hezbollah’s arsenal (in addition to RPG rockets):</p>



<p><strong>Sagger</strong> – up to 3,000 meters. First generation (see explanation below) – manually guided via wire.<br><strong>Fagot</strong> – up to 2,500 meters. Second generation (see explanation below) – wire-guided.<br><strong>Metis</strong> – up to 1,000 meters. Second generation – wire-guided (capable of launching from enclosed spaces due to a two-stage activation, where the motor ignites only after the missile has been launched by an initial charge).<br><strong>Milan</strong> – up to 3,000 meters. Second generation – wire-guided.<br><strong>Toophan</strong> – up to 3,500 meters. Second generation.<br><strong>Konkurs</strong> – up to 4,000 meters. Second generation.<br><strong>Kornet</strong> – up to 5,500 meters (improved version up to 10,000 meters), second generation, laser beam-riding (without wire).<br><strong>Almas</strong> – up to 16 kilometers. An Iranian version of the Israeli Spike missile. Operates on the “fire-and-forget” principle (third generation). Ballistic movement toward the target (top-attack). Equipped with a camera transmitting back during flight.</p>



<p>In the first generation, the operator (the shooter) must control, from the moment of launch until impact, the position of the sight relative to the target, the position of the missile itself, and physically track the target’s location. In the second generation, the operator must control the position of the sight relative to the target and physically track the target’s location, but there is no need to control the missile’s position during its flight.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://israel-alma.org/hezbollahs-anti-tank-missile-arsenal-capabilities-and-threat-assessment/">Hezbollah’s Anti‑Tank Missile Arsenal: Capabilities and Threat Assessment</a> appeared first on <a href="https://israel-alma.org">Alma Research and Education Center</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
